{
  "success": true,
  "data": "{
  "database": "us_data_center_large_load_tariffs",
  "schema": "public",
  "table_count": 1,
  "tables": [
    {
      "name": "us_data_center_large_load_tariffs_table",
      "description": "The columns contain tariffs for data centers: 'state' - states; 'utility'-utility operating company name; 'tariff'-name of tariff; 'status'-pending/proposed, or approved(approved includes effective tariffs);'year'-year of status;'sector_or_segment'-customer applicability and focus, as defined in proposal or approved tariff;'minimum_demand_mw';'minimum_load_factor';'utility_type';'iso_rto';'narrative_highlights';'references_dockets';'minimum_contract_term'-The minimum initial contract term for service under this tariff, if any;'load_ramp_up_period'-The number of years, typically starting at full provision of service, over which the customer is assumed to be growing its operations and may not yet require its full contract capacity. Some tariffs specify different billing demand terms during and after the load ramp-up period. The load ramp-up period may be included in, or additive to, the initial contract term; check tariff documents for details.;'minimum_bill_as_a_percentage_of_contract_capacity'-Sets a minimum customer demand charge equal to a set percentage of contracted monthly capacity (% of MW). In effect, customers pay for a guaranteed amount of reserved capacity, even if unused. Minimum bill may also be set relative to historic usage; several examples are noted in this database;'financial_assurance_and_contributions'-Selected key financial assurances and contributions required to take service under the tariff.Note: CIAC stands for contribution in aid of construction; 'customer_pays_utility_study_costs'-Customers taking service under the tariff are required to pay for utility interconnection study and/or other upfront assessment costs;'contract_modification_provisions'-Options and opportunities for customers to request contract modifications, if specified in the tariff. This database notes: Change/Exit Notice Period: Defines a time period in which a customer may give notice or request a change to their contract capacity (i.e., increase or decrease), terminate service on the large load tariff, and/or take service on a different tariff. Change/Exit Fees: Defines fees a customer may need to pay to the utility to reduce their contract capacity during a particular time period, terminate service on the large load tariff, and/or take service on a different one. Security Reductions/Release: Defines or allows options for the utility to revise the customer\u2019s current deposit or collateral requirements, such as to reflect customer operational changes, changes to the financial condition of the customer or guarantor, market conditions, etc.; 'energy_transition_provisions'-Tariff includes options for customers to pursue energy transition objectives, or explicitly references the availability of separate riders for this purpose. These may include time-of-use (TOU) pricing, interruptible service agreements, clean or renewable energy riders, Clean Transition Tariffs, and other related mechanisms. Several examples are noted in this database."
    }
  ]
}",
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {
    "method": "show_tables"
  }
}

